  overview: `For eleven acts the story has been leaning forward. A promise was whispered in a ruined garden — that one born of the woman would one day crush the serpent (Genesis 3:15). It was sharpened into a family (the offspring of Abraham), a nation, a law, a land, a throne (the son of David), and a long ache voiced by the prophets — a coming King, a suffering Servant, a child called *Immanuel*, "God with us." Centuries passed. The promises piled up like banked embers. And then, in the fullness of time, the promise stopped being a promise and became a person. **The Word became flesh.** The Author of the story walked onto its stage.

The four Gospels tell what happened. A young woman in an unremarkable town says yes to an impossible word. A baby is born in Bethlehem, the city of David, and laid in a feeding trough because there was no room. Thirty quiet years pass. Then a carpenter from Nazareth is baptized in the Jordan, driven into the wilderness, and emerges announcing that the kingdom of God has come near. For about three years he teaches as no one ever taught, heals the sick, touches the untouchable, feeds the hungry, stills storms, forgives sins, and gathers the broken and the unimportant around a new way of being human — the last first, the poor blessed, enemies loved. He claims, in word and deed, an authority that belongs to God alone.

It cannot end quietly. The collision with the powers of his day carries him to a Roman cross, where he dies with a cry that sounds like surrender and turns out to be victory: *"It is finished."* He is buried. And on the third day the tomb is empty, the grave-clothes folded, and he is seen — alive — by his stunned friends, who will spend the rest of their lives, and lose them, telling the world what they saw. Before he ascends, he sends them out to every nation with the news that death has been defeated and God's reign has begun.

This is the center of the whole library — the hinge on which history turns. Here every scarlet thread is gathered into one hand: the seed of the woman, the offspring of Abraham, the Passover lamb, the prophet greater than Moses, the son of David, the suffering Servant of Isaiah, the Son of Man of Daniel — all of them, at last, one person. To meet him is the reason the journey exists. Everything before points forward to him; everything after flows back from him. This is the brightest screen because it is the brightest fact: God did not stay far off. He came near. He came as one of us. He came for us.`,

  context: `The word *gospel* (Greek *euangelion*) did not begin as the name of a book. It was a royal announcement — the heralded "good news" that a king had been born, or a victory won, or a new reign begun. So when four early Christian writers each titled their account a "gospel," they were making a claim before they told a single story: this is the news of a King and a kingdom. We have not one gospel but four, and the church kept all four rather than blending them into one, because a single life this large needed more than one angle. They are four portraits of one face, four witnesses to one life — and where they differ in detail, they testify, as honest witnesses do, from where each one stood.

Each portrait has its own light. **Matthew** paints Jesus as the **King** and the fulfillment of Israel's hope: he opens with a genealogy reaching back to Abraham and David, and again and again says a thing happened "that it might be fulfilled." Jesus is the new Moses who gives a new law from a mountain; the promised Messiah of the Jewish Scriptures. **Mark**, likely the earliest and the briefest, paints the **Servant** — urgent, breathless (his favorite word is "immediately"), showing a Jesus more in action than in speech, on the move toward the cross, who "came not to be served, but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many." **Luke**, a careful historian and companion of Paul who also wrote the book of Acts, paints the **Savior of all** — lifting up the poor, the outsider, women, Samaritans, tax collectors, the lost; his Jesus is the friend of sinners come "to seek and to save that which was lost." **John**, written latest and most reflectively, paints the **divine Son** — opening not in Bethlehem but in eternity ("In the beginning was the Word"), built around seven signs and seven "I AM" sayings, written plainly "that you may believe that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of God; and that believing, you may have life in his name."

On authorship and date, the tradition and the scholarship can be stated fairly side by side. From the early second century the church named the authors: **Matthew** the tax-collector apostle; **Mark** recording the preaching of Peter; **Luke** the physician and traveling companion of Paul; **John** the beloved disciple. Most scholars date Mark to around AD 65–70 and the others between roughly AD 70 and 95, while a number of conservative scholars argue for earlier dates, some before AD 70 — but on any reckoning the Gospels were composed within living memory of the events, drawing on eyewitness testimony, when people who had known Jesus could still confirm or contradict the accounts. The differences among them are not the marks of fiction but of testimony: four real witnesses, remembering one unforgettable life, each telling the truth in his own voice.`,

