      name: 'Pontius Pilate',
      oneLine: 'The Roman governor who found no fault in Jesus — and condemned him anyway.',
      bio: `Pontius Pilate was the Roman prefect of Judea (roughly AD 26–36), the imperial official who held the power of life and death. When the religious leaders brought Jesus to him demanding execution, Pilate examined him and concluded, more than once, *"I find no basis for a charge against him"* (John 18:38). His exchange with Jesus produced one of history's most haunting questions — *"What is truth?"* — asked, tragically, of the One who had just called himself the truth.

Yet Pilate is a study in the cowardice of expedience. Caught between his own judgment and the pressure of a hostile crowd that threatened to report him to Caesar, he chose his career over justice. He had Jesus flogged, presented him to the mob — *"Behold, the man!"* — and then, washing his hands in a futile gesture of innocence, handed over a man he knew to be guiltless to be crucified (Matthew 27:11–26). His name is fixed forever in the creed the church confesses — Jesus "suffered under Pontius Pilate" — a permanent reminder that the kingdom of God was opposed not only by open enemies but by those who knew better and would not act.`,
